const BANK = [
// VALUES & SOCIETY
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"Which of the following best describes a fundamental British value?",o:["Loyalty to a single political party","Tolerance and respect for others","Speaking only English in public","Practising Christianity"],a:1,exp:"The fundamental values include democracy, rule of law, individual liberty, and mutual respect and tolerance for those with different faiths and beliefs."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What does 'rule of law' mean in the UK?",o:["The government can make any law it wishes","Everyone — including the government — must obey the law","Laws are made by judges rather than Parliament","The police decide which laws are enforced"],a:1,exp:"The rule of law means no one is above the law, including the government. Disputes are settled by independent courts."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"Which of these is NOT a fundamental principle of British life?",o:["Democracy","Rule of law","Compulsory religious observance","Individual liberty"],a:2,exp:"The four fundamental principles are: democracy, rule of law, individual liberty, and mutual respect and tolerance. Religious observance is a personal choice."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What does 'democracy' mean in the UK?",o:["The monarch makes all decisions","Citizens elect representatives to make decisions on their behalf","Laws are decided only by referendums","Only property owners may vote"],a:1,exp:"Democracy means citizens choose their representatives through free and fair elections. The UK is a representative democracy."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"Which organisation oversees UK elections to ensure they are fair?",o:["The Home Office","The Electoral Commission","The House of Lords","The Boundary Commission"],a:1,exp:"The Electoral Commission is the independent body responsible for overseeing elections and referendums and regulating party finances."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What does freedom of speech mean in the UK?",o:["You can say absolutely anything without consequence","You can express opinions freely within the law","Only journalists have freedom of speech","Freedom of speech only applies in Parliament"],a:1,exp:"Freedom of speech means expressing opinions without government censorship. It has legal limits — for example, inciting hatred is illegal."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"Jury service is an obligation for eligible UK citizens. Who qualifies?",o:["Only homeowners","Only those with no criminal convictions","Citizens aged 18--70 on the electoral roll, subject to certain exemptions","All adults over 25"],a:2,exp:"Any UK citizen aged 18--70 who is registered to vote can be called for jury service. Failing to respond is a criminal offence."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What is the role of the civil service?",o:["To campaign for the governing party","To implement government policy impartially, regardless of which party is in power","To elect the Prime Minister","To write new laws"],a:1,exp:"The civil service is politically neutral and implements government policy. Civil servants serve whichever party forms the government."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"Which of the following is a right AND responsibility of a UK citizen?",o:["To demand benefits from the state","To vote in elections and serve on a jury if called","To fly the Union Flag at all times","To speak only English in public"],a:1,exp:"Voting and jury service are both rights and responsibilities. The others are not legal obligations."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What does 'individual liberty' mean as a British value?",o:["Everyone must obey the government without question","People are free to live as they choose within the law","Only British-born citizens have full freedom","Liberty is limited to property owners"],a:1,exp:"Individual liberty means people can make their own choices and live as they wish, as long as they stay within the law and respect others' rights."},

// BRITISH HISTORY
{cat:"British History",q:"Who defeated Harold II at the Battle of Hastings in 1066?",o:["Richard I","King Canute","William, Duke of Normandy","Harald Hardrada"],a:2,exp:"William, Duke of Normandy, won the Battle of Hastings in October 1066 and became William I — William the Conqueror."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Which king signed Magna Carta in 1215?",o:["Henry VIII","King John","Richard II","Henry II"],a:1,exp:"King John signed Magna Carta at Runnymede in 1215 under pressure from rebellious barons. It limited royal power and established the rule of law."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the significance of the Glorious Revolution of 1688?",o:["England became a republic","Parliament's power over the monarch was firmly established","Scotland and England unified","The Church of England was abolished"],a:1,exp:"The Glorious Revolution brought William of Orange to the throne and led to the Bill of Rights (1689), establishing Parliament's supremacy."},
{cat:"British History",q:"In which century did the Industrial Revolution begin in Britain?",o:["16th century","17th century","18th century","19th century"],a:2,exp:"The Industrial Revolution began in Britain in the 18th century. Britain was the first industrialised nation, driven by textile mills, steam power and iron production."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the main cause of the English Civil War (1642--51)?",o:["A religious dispute between Protestants and Catholics","Conflict between Charles I and Parliament over the limits of royal power","Scotland's attempt to invade England","France's invasion of southern England"],a:1,exp:"The Civil War was primarily about whether the King or Parliament held ultimate authority. Charles I believed in the divine right of kings."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What happened to King Charles I after the English Civil War?",o:["He was exiled to France","He was executed in 1649","He was imprisoned for life","He abdicated and fled to Scotland"],a:1,exp:"Charles I was tried by Parliament for treason and executed in January 1649. England became a republic (Commonwealth) under Oliver Cromwell."},
{cat:"British History",q:"The Acts of Union 1707 united which two countries?",o:["England and Ireland","England and Wales","England and Scotland","Great Britain and Ireland"],a:2,exp:"The Acts of Union 1707 joined England and Scotland to form the Kingdom of Great Britain. Wales had been incorporated into England by earlier legislation."},
{cat:"British History",q:"When was the current Union Flag created?",o:["1606","1707","1801","1850"],a:2,exp:"The current Union Flag was created in 1801 when Ireland joined Great Britain, adding St Patrick's Cross to the design."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What major social reform occurred in Britain in 1948?",o:["The founding of NATO","The creation of the NHS","The Festival of Britain","Women gaining equal voting rights"],a:1,exp:"The National Health Service (NHS) was founded in 1948 by the post-war Labour government — one of the greatest social reforms in British history."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the suffragette movement?",o:["A campaign for workers' rights","A campaign for women's right to vote","A campaign to extend voting to working-class men","An early environmental movement"],a:1,exp:"Suffragettes campaigned militantly for women's voting rights. Key figures include Emmeline Pankhurst and her daughters Sylvia and Christabel."},
{cat:"British History",q:"In what year did women over 30 first receive the right to vote?",o:["1903","1911","1918","1928"],a:2,exp:"The Representation of the People Act 1918 gave women over 30 with property qualifications the right to vote. Equal voting rights came in 1928."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Which battle in 1415 saw Henry V defeat France?",o:["Battle of Bosworth Field","Battle of Agincourt","Battle of Crécy","Battle of Poitiers"],a:1,exp:"The Battle of Agincourt (1415) was a famous English victory during the Hundred Years War, celebrated in Shakespeare's 'Henry V'."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Who was the first Tudor monarch?",o:["Henry VIII","Henry VII","Edward VI","Elizabeth I"],a:1,exp:"Henry VII became the first Tudor king after defeating Richard III at the Battle of Bosworth Field in 1485, ending the Wars of the Roses."},
{cat:"British History",q:"The Domesday Book was commissioned by which king?",o:["Harold II","Edward the Confessor","William I","Henry I"],a:2,exp:"William I commissioned the Domesday Book in 1085--86 — a comprehensive survey of England to assess land ownership and tax obligations."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Who led the Parliamentarians during the English Civil War?",o:["John Locke","Oliver Cromwell","Thomas Cromwell","Duke of Marlborough"],a:1,exp:"Oliver Cromwell was the leading Parliamentary military commander and later became Lord Protector after the execution of Charles I."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Who wrote the plays 'Hamlet', 'Macbeth' and 'A Midsummer Night's Dream'?",o:["Geoffrey Chaucer","Christopher Marlowe","William Shakespeare","John Milton"],a:2,exp:"William Shakespeare (1564--1616) is widely regarded as the greatest writer in the English language. He was born in Stratford-upon-Avon."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Which English queen reigned for over 70 years until 2022?",o:["Victoria","Elizabeth II","Elizabeth I","Mary I"],a:1,exp:"Queen Elizabeth II reigned from 1952 until her death in 2022 — over 70 years — making her the longest-reigning British monarch in history."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What century did the Great Fire of London occur?",o:["15th century","16th century","17th century","18th century"],a:2,exp:"The Great Fire of London occurred in September 1666 — the 17th century. Sir Christopher Wren oversaw much of the rebuilding, including St Paul's Cathedral."},
{cat:"British History",q:"The Magna Carta (1215) primarily established what?",o:["A written constitution for England","That the king was subject to the rule of law and certain rights were guaranteed","Free elections for all citizens","The independence of the Church from the state"],a:1,exp:"Magna Carta established that the king was subject to the rule of law — a cornerstone of the British constitution. It did not create a full constitution or free elections."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Which battle ended the Wars of the Roses in 1485?",o:["Battle of Agincourt","Battle of Naseby","Battle of Bosworth Field","Battle of Flodden"],a:2,exp:"The Battle of Bosworth Field (1485) ended the Wars of the Roses when Henry Tudor defeated Richard III, becoming Henry VII — the first Tudor king."},

// A MODERN SOCIETY
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"Which of the following is true about the BBC?",o:["It is owned by a private company","It is funded entirely by government taxes","It is a public broadcaster funded mainly by the licence fee","It operates only online"],a:2,exp:"The BBC is a public broadcaster funded primarily by the TV licence fee. It was established by Royal Charter and is editorially independent of the government."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What is a local council?",o:["A committee advising the Prime Minister","An elected body providing local services","A branch of the NHS","A community group with no official power"],a:1,exp:"Local councils are elected bodies responsible for local services including refuse collection, parks, planning, and local roads."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"The 2012 Olympic Games were held in which UK city?",o:["Manchester","Birmingham","London","Edinburgh"],a:2,exp:"The 2012 Summer Olympics were held in London at the Olympic Park in Stratford, east London — widely regarded as a great success."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"Who was Isaac Newton?",o:["A Scottish philosopher who wrote about democracy","An English scientist known for laws of motion and gravity","A Welsh mathematician who invented calculus alone","An Irish physicist who discovered electricity"],a:1,exp:"Isaac Newton (1643--1727) was born in Lincolnshire. He formulated laws of motion and universal gravitation and is considered one of history's most influential scientists."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What does the term 'multicultural society' describe?",o:["A policy requiring one national culture","Co-existence of many different cultures and ethnicities","A system where each ethnic group lives separately","An EU immigration framework"],a:1,exp:"A multicultural society is one where people of different ethnic, cultural, and religious backgrounds co-exist. The UK is one of the world's most diverse societies."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What is the National Living Wage?",o:["A suggested pay guide for large businesses","The legally required minimum hourly pay for workers aged 23 and over","A benefit paid to low-income families","The average wage across the UK"],a:1,exp:"The National Living Wage is the legal minimum wage for workers aged 23 and over. Younger workers have separate minimum wage rates."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"Glastonbury, held annually in Somerset, is best known as what kind of event?",o:["A Highland games festival","A music and performing arts festival","A Welsh literary festival","A royal flower show"],a:1,exp:"Glastonbury is a major outdoor music and performing arts festival held in Somerset, England. It is one of the largest and most famous music festivals in the world."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What percentage of people in England and Wales identified as Christian in the 2011 Census?",o:["About 30%","About 59%","About 70%","About 45%"],a:1,exp:"In the 2011 Census, 59% identified as Christian. This fell to 46% in the 2021 Census. The Life in the UK handbook references the 2011 figure."},

// GOVERNMENT & LAW
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"How is the Prime Minister chosen?",o:["Directly elected by the public","Elected by the House of Lords","The leader of the party with the most seats in the House of Commons","Appointed by the monarch independently"],a:2,exp:"The PM is the leader of the party winning the most Commons seats, then formally appointed by the monarch."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the role of the House of Lords?",o:["The most powerful chamber — it overrides the Commons","It scrutinises and can amend or delay Commons legislation","It elects the Prime Minister","It controls the national budget"],a:1,exp:"The Lords reviews legislation from the Commons and can suggest amendments or delay (but not permanently block) bills. The Commons has ultimate authority."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the maximum term of a UK Parliament?",o:["4 years","5 years","6 years","3 years"],a:1,exp:"A general election must take place within 5 years. The Prime Minister may call an earlier election."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"Which is the highest court in the UK?",o:["The Court of Appeal","The High Court","The Crown Court","The Supreme Court"],a:3,exp:"The UK Supreme Court, established in 2009, is the highest court of appeal. It replaced the Appellate Committee of the House of Lords."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What voting system is used for UK general elections?",o:["Proportional representation","Alternative vote","First past the post","Single transferable vote"],a:2,exp:"UK general elections use first past the post (FPTP) — the candidate with the most votes in each constituency wins, even without a majority."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"Who appoints judges in the UK?",o:["The Prime Minister directly","The monarch, on advice of the independent Judicial Appointments Commission","Parliament by vote","The Lord Chief Justice alone"],a:1,exp:"Judges are appointed by the monarch on advice of the Judicial Appointments Commission — an independent body ensuring judicial independence from politicians."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What body is responsible for making UK-wide laws?",o:["The Scottish Parliament","The UK Parliament at Westminster","The European Union","The Supreme Court"],a:1,exp:"The UK Parliament at Westminster is sovereign and legislates for the entire UK. Devolved assemblies handle devolved matters only."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the 'Speaker' of the House of Commons?",o:["The Prime Minister's spokesperson","The MP who chairs debates and maintains order in the Commons","The leader of the opposition","The minister who reads out government statements"],a:1,exp:"The Speaker is an MP elected by fellow MPs to chair debates impartially. Once elected, they give up party affiliation."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What does 'innocent until proven guilty' mean?",o:["Only the wealthy can prove innocence","The prosecution must prove guilt — the defendant need not prove innocence","A judge must always believe the defendant","The police decide guilt before trial"],a:1,exp:"This is the presumption of innocence. The burden of proof lies with the prosecution to prove guilt beyond reasonable doubt."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the role of a jury in a Crown Court trial?",o:["To decide the sentence","To hear evidence and decide guilty or not guilty","To assist the judge in writing the law","To prosecute the defendant"],a:1,exp:"A jury of 12 members of the public decides the verdict. The judge decides the sentence if the defendant is found guilty."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What are the devolved governments of the UK?",o:["City councils of London, Manchester and Birmingham","The Scottish Parliament, Welsh Senedd, and Northern Ireland Assembly","Regional development agencies","County councils across England"],a:1,exp:"Devolved power has been granted to the Scottish Parliament, Welsh Senedd, and Northern Ireland Assembly. England has no separate parliament."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is an MP's 'surgery'?",o:["Free medical consultations for constituents","Regular meetings where MPs hear constituents' concerns","Party membership recruitment sessions","Training sessions for new MPs"],a:1,exp:"MPs hold constituency surgeries — meetings where local people raise concerns about issues such as housing, benefits, or immigration."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is council tax used to fund?",o:["National defence","Local government services like rubbish collection, schools and roads","The NHS exclusively","Central government departments"],a:1,exp:"Council tax funds local services including refuse collection, libraries, parks, local roads, and contributes to local police and fire services."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is Hansard?",o:["The official record of Parliamentary debates","A UK political journal","The government's annual budget","A register of lobbyists"],a:0,exp:"Hansard is the verbatim official record of all debates and proceedings in both Houses of Parliament, published online."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the role of the Leader of the Opposition?",o:["To support the government's legislation","To lead the largest non-government party and scrutinise the PM","To chair the House of Commons","To advise the monarch"],a:1,exp:"The Leader of the Opposition leads a 'shadow cabinet' that scrutinises the government and presents an alternative programme, notably in Prime Minister's Questions."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is a 'by-election'?",o:["An election to choose a local council leader","An election when an MP's seat becomes vacant between general elections","A second round if no candidate wins outright","An election in Scotland or Wales only"],a:1,exp:"A by-election is held when an MP vacates their seat between general elections due to death, resignation, or disqualification."},

// NATIONS & SYMBOLS
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the national flower of England?",o:["Daffodil","Thistle","Rose","Shamrock"],a:2,exp:"The rose is the national flower of England. The red rose is also the emblem of the Labour Party."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the national flower of Scotland?",o:["Heather","Thistle","Bluebell","Primrose"],a:1,exp:"The thistle has been Scotland's emblem since the reign of Alexander III (1249--1286)."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the national flower of Wales?",o:["Leek","Shamrock","Daffodil","Rose"],a:2,exp:"The daffodil is the national flower of Wales. The leek is the national emblem — both symbols are associated with Wales."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"Who is the patron saint of Scotland?",o:["St George","St David","St Patrick","St Andrew"],a:3,exp:"St Andrew is the patron saint of Scotland. His feast day is 30 November. The Scottish flag is based on his cross."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What does the Union Flag combine?",o:["The flags of England, Scotland and Wales","The crosses of St George, St Andrew and St Patrick","The symbols of the monarchy, Parliament and Church","The flags of all Commonwealth nations"],a:1,exp:"The Union Flag combines St George's Cross (England), St Andrew's Cross (Scotland) and St Patrick's Cross (Ireland). Wales is not separately represented."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"Which language is spoken in Wales alongside English?",o:["Gaelic","Cornish","Welsh","Manx"],a:2,exp:"Welsh (Cymraeg) is an official language in Wales alongside English. About 30% of Welsh people speak Welsh."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What does the dragon on the Welsh flag represent?",o:["Roman occupation of Wales","An ancient symbol of Wales from mythology and history","It was added to honour Henry VIII","Wales's industrial heritage"],a:1,exp:"The red dragon (Y Ddraig Goch) is an ancient symbol of Wales. The current flag became official in 1959."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"On which date is St George's Day celebrated?",o:["1 March","17 March","23 April","30 November"],a:2,exp:"St George's Day is 23 April. Patron saints' days: St David (1 March -- Wales), St Patrick (17 March -- Ireland), St George (23 April -- England), St Andrew (30 November -- Scotland)."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the Eisteddfod?",o:["A Scottish Highland games event","A Welsh festival of music, literature and the arts","An English folk dance competition","A Northern Irish cultural festival"],a:1,exp:"The Eisteddfod is a Welsh cultural festival primarily in the Welsh language. The National Eisteddfod alternates between north and south Wales."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What instrument is traditionally associated with Welsh culture?",o:["Bagpipes","The fiddle","The harp","The lute"],a:2,exp:"The harp is closely associated with Wales. The national eisteddfod prominently features the harp. Wales is sometimes called 'the land of song'."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What flower is worn on Remembrance Day?",o:["White lily","Red poppy","Bluebell","Daffodil"],a:1,exp:"The red poppy is worn around Remembrance Day (11 November). The tradition began after World War I, inspired by the poem 'In Flanders Fields'."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the name of the devolved parliament of Wales?",o:["The Welsh Assembly","The Welsh Parliament (Senedd Cymru)","The Welsh Congress","The Cymru Council"],a:1,exp:"The Welsh Parliament is officially the Senedd Cymru. Previously called the National Assembly for Wales, it has powers over health, education and other devolved matters."},

// EVERYDAY LIFE
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is the NHS?",o:["A private health insurance scheme","The National Health Service — free healthcare at the point of use, funded by taxation","A network of private hospitals","A charitable organisation running hospitals"],a:1,exp:"The NHS was founded in 1948 and provides healthcare free at the point of use for all UK residents, funded by taxation and National Insurance."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"At what age can a person in England marry without parental consent?",o:["16","17","18","21"],a:2,exp:"The legal marriage age without parental consent is 18 in England, Wales and Northern Ireland. Scotland introduced this change in 2023."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is a National Insurance number?",o:["A number to access NHS services","A unique number tracking your tax and NI contributions","A number required to vote","A bank account reference"],a:1,exp:"A National Insurance number is a unique reference ensuring your tax and NI contributions are recorded. It qualifies you for benefits and the state pension."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is the minimum legal requirement for UK car insurance?",o:["Comprehensive insurance","Third-party insurance","Fully comprehensive with breakdown cover","Employer's liability insurance"],a:1,exp:"Drivers are legally required to have at least third-party insurance. Driving without insurance is a criminal offence."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is the minimum school participation age in England?",o:["15","16","17","18"],a:3,exp:"Young people in England must stay in education or training until 18. This could be school, college, apprenticeships, or part-time training alongside work."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is a GP?",o:["A Government Prescriptions service","A General Practitioner — a local family doctor","A Grade Points academic system","A Government Pension scheme"],a:1,exp:"A GP (General Practitioner) is a local family doctor providing primary care, referrals to specialists, and prescriptions."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is the purpose of a TV licence?",o:["A tax on all electronic devices","Required to watch live TV or use BBC iPlayer — it funds the BBC","A voluntary ITV subscription","Allows households to record programmes"],a:1,exp:"A TV licence is required to watch any live television or use BBC iPlayer. It funds the BBC's public broadcasting services."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"How old must you be to buy alcohol in the UK?",o:["16","17","18","21"],a:2,exp:"You must be 18 or over to buy alcohol. It is also an offence to buy alcohol for someone under 18."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What does 999 connect you to?",o:["NHS non-emergency line","Police non-emergency line","Emergency services — police, fire, ambulance","The coastguard only"],a:2,exp:"999 is the emergency services number. For non-emergency police use 101; for non-emergency NHS advice use 111."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is the 'right to buy' scheme?",o:["The right to buy shares in the stock market","A scheme letting council house tenants buy their home at a discount","A consumer right to return goods within 30 days","The right to buy Crown land"],a:1,exp:"Right to Buy, introduced in 1980 under Thatcher, allowed council tenants to buy their homes at a significant discount, dramatically increasing home ownership."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What does 'GCSE' stand for?",o:["General Certificate of Secondary Education","General Certificate of School Examination","Government-Certified Secondary Education","General Curriculum Standard Examination"],a:0,exp:"GCSE stands for General Certificate of Secondary Education — exams taken by students in England, Wales and Northern Ireland at around age 16."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What does Ofsted do?",o:["Manages the Office for Standards in Education — inspecting schools in England","Regulates financial services","Oversees the government health department","Supports children in care"],a:0,exp:"Ofsted (Office for Standards in Education) inspects schools and other education providers in England, rating them Outstanding, Good, Requires Improvement or Inadequate."},

// UK & WORLD
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What is the Commonwealth?",o:["A military alliance led by the UK","A trading bloc replacing the EU","A voluntary association of 56 countries, mostly former British territories","Countries that still use the pound sterling"],a:2,exp:"The Commonwealth is a voluntary association of 56 independent countries. Members cooperate on trade, development and democracy but have no formal obligations."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"The UK is a permanent member of which global body with a veto?",o:["The G7","The NATO security committee","The UN Security Council","The World Trade Organisation"],a:2,exp:"The UK is one of five permanent UN Security Council members (with the USA, Russia, China and France), each holding veto power."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What does NATO stand for?",o:["North American Treaty Organisation","North Atlantic Treaty Organisation","National Alliance of Treaty Obligations","Nordic and Atlantic Trade Organisation"],a:1,exp:"NATO stands for North Atlantic Treaty Organisation. The UK is a founding member. Under Article 5, an attack on one member is treated as an attack on all."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"When did the UK formally leave the European Union?",o:["January 2019","January 2020","June 2016","December 2020"],a:1,exp:"The UK formally left the EU on 31 January 2020, following the June 2016 referendum result (52% voted to leave). The transition period ended 31 December 2020."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What currency does the UK use?",o:["The euro","The pound sterling","The US dollar","The crown"],a:1,exp:"The UK uses the pound sterling (£, GBP). It did not adopt the euro when it was introduced."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What is the G7?",o:["A group of 7 of the world's largest economies","A NATO sub-committee","A UN Security Council working group","A Commonwealth trade body"],a:0,exp:"The G7 is a group of seven major advanced economies: the UK, USA, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, and Japan. The EU also participates."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What did the UK help found after World War II to promote peace?",o:["The EU","The United Nations","The Commonwealth","NATO"],a:1,exp:"The UK was a founding member of the United Nations, established in 1945 to maintain international peace and security."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"The Falkland Islands are an overseas territory of which country?",o:["Australia","New Zealand","The United Kingdom","Canada"],a:2,exp:"The Falkland Islands are a British Overseas Territory. The UK and Argentina fought a war over them in 1982, which the UK won."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What does 'the special relationship' refer to?",o:["The relationship between England and Scotland","Close diplomatic, military and cultural ties between the UK and the USA","The UK's trading relationship with the Commonwealth","The UK's unique membership of NATO and the UN"],a:1,exp:"The 'special relationship' describes the exceptionally close ties between the UK and the United States. The term was popularised by Winston Churchill."},

// ── BRITISH HISTORY (harder) ──────────────────────────────
{cat:"British History",q:"In what year was the Magna Carta signed?",o:["1066","1215","1265","1314"],a:1,exp:"Magna Carta was signed by King John in 1215 at Runnymede, on the banks of the River Thames."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the 'Black Death'?",o:["A volcanic eruption that affected Northern England","A bubonic plague that killed around a third of the UK population in the 14th century","A series of famines in medieval Ireland","A name for the great smogs of industrial London"],a:1,exp:"The Black Death (bubonic plague) arrived in England in 1348 and killed around a third of the population. It had enormous social and economic consequences."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Which monarch established the Church of England by breaking from Rome?",o:["Edward VI","Mary I","Henry VIII","Elizabeth I"],a:2,exp:"Henry VIII broke from the Roman Catholic Church in the 1530s, primarily to annul his marriage to Catherine of Aragon. He made himself Supreme Head of the Church of England."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the Habeas Corpus Act of 1679?",o:["A law granting women the right to own property","A law preventing the monarch from raising taxes without Parliament","A law requiring that a prisoner must be brought before a court — preventing unlawful imprisonment","A law establishing the Church of England"],a:2,exp:"Habeas Corpus (1679) established that anyone imprisoned must be brought before a court to determine whether their detention is lawful — a fundamental protection against arbitrary imprisonment."},
{cat:"British History",q:"The 'Reformation' in 16th century England primarily involved what?",o:["A reform of the voting system","The break from the Roman Catholic Church and establishment of Protestant Christianity","A series of reforms to Parliament's powers","The reorganisation of the English legal system"],a:1,exp:"The English Reformation was the break from Rome and the Catholic Church, beginning under Henry VIII and continuing under Edward VI and Elizabeth I, establishing Protestantism as England's official religion."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the significance of the Battle of Britain in 1940?",o:["Britain invaded France to liberate Paris","The RAF successfully defended Britain against the German Luftwaffe air campaign","Britain defeated the German navy in the North Sea","British forces captured Berlin"],a:1,exp:"The Battle of Britain was an air campaign by Nazi Germany to gain air superiority over Britain. The RAF's successful defence prevented a German invasion and is considered a turning point in WW2."},
{cat:"British History",q:"In which year did the First World War end?",o:["1916","1917","1918","1919"],a:2,exp:"World War One ended on 11 November 1918, when an armistice was signed. This date is commemorated annually as Remembrance Day."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Which prime minister led Britain during most of the Second World War?",o:["Neville Chamberlain","Clement Attlee","Anthony Eden","Winston Churchill"],a:3,exp:"Winston Churchill became Prime Minister in May 1940 and led Britain through most of WW2. He is widely regarded as one of the greatest wartime leaders in history."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What did the Beveridge Report of 1942 propose?",o:["A plan for post-war military alliances","A welfare state providing social security 'from the cradle to the grave'","The nationalisation of all British industry","A new written constitution for Britain"],a:1,exp:"The Beveridge Report (1942) proposed a comprehensive welfare state tackling the 'five giants': Want, Disease, Ignorance, Squalor and Idleness. It laid the foundations for the NHS and post-war welfare state."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the name of the ship on which the Pilgrim Fathers sailed to America in 1620?",o:["The Golden Hind","The Endeavour","The Mayflower","The Victory"],a:2,exp:"The Mayflower carried the Pilgrim Fathers — English Puritan settlers — from Plymouth to America in 1620, where they founded Plymouth Colony in what is now Massachusetts."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Who was the first Prime Minister of Great Britain?",o:["William Pitt the Younger","Robert Walpole","William Gladstone","Benjamin Disraeli"],a:1,exp:"Robert Walpole is generally regarded as the first Prime Minister, serving from 1721 to 1742 under George I and George II."},
{cat:"British History",q:"The Chartist movement of the 19th century campaigned for what?",o:["The abolition of slavery","Political reform including votes for all men and a secret ballot","Women's right to vote","The independence of Scotland"],a:1,exp:"The Chartists (1838--1857) were a working-class movement campaigning for democratic reforms: votes for all men, secret ballots, equal constituencies, and payment for MPs."},
{cat:"British History",q:"In which year did women achieve equal voting rights with men in the UK?",o:["1918","1921","1928","1932"],a:2,exp:"The Equal Franchise Act 1928 gave all women over 21 the vote on equal terms with men. Previously (since 1918), only women over 30 who met property qualifications could vote."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the significance of the Reform Act 1832?",o:["It abolished the House of Lords","It extended the right to vote to more men and removed 'rotten boroughs'","It gave women the right to vote for the first time","It created the position of Prime Minister"],a:1,exp:"The Great Reform Act 1832 was a landmark law that extended the vote to more middle-class men, redistributed Parliamentary seats from depopulated 'rotten boroughs' to growing industrial cities."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Which explorer, backed by Queen Elizabeth I, circumnavigated the globe between 1577 and 1580?",o:["Walter Raleigh","James Cook","Francis Drake","Humphrey Gilbert"],a:2,exp:"Sir Francis Drake completed the second circumnavigation of the globe (1577--80) and was the first Englishman to do so. He was later vice admiral during the defeat of the Spanish Armada in 1588."},

// ── GOVERNMENT & LAW (harder) ────────────────────────────
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the difference between criminal law and civil law in the UK?",o:["Criminal law is for adults, civil law is for minors","Criminal law involves offences against the state or society; civil law resolves disputes between individuals","Criminal law is English law; civil law is Scottish law","There is no difference — they use the same courts"],a:1,exp:"Criminal law covers offences against the state (e.g. theft, assault) prosecuted by the Crown. Civil law resolves disputes between individuals or organisations (e.g. contracts, property). They use different courts."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the Oath of Allegiance sworn by new citizens?",o:["A promise to obey all UK laws at all times","A pledge of loyalty to the Crown, and to uphold the rights and freedoms of the UK","A commitment to serve in the armed forces if required","An agreement to pay taxes and contribute to society"],a:1,exp:"New citizens swear (or affirm) an Oath of Allegiance to the monarch and a pledge to uphold the democratic values of the UK at a citizenship ceremony."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"Which of these is a devolved matter — meaning Scotland, Wales or N. Ireland decide it for themselves?",o:["Foreign policy","Defence","Health","Immigration"],a:2,exp:"Health is a devolved matter. Foreign policy, defence and immigration are reserved to the UK Parliament at Westminster and apply across the whole UK."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the purpose of the Human Rights Act 1998?",o:["It created a written constitution for the UK","It incorporated the European Convention on Human Rights into UK law","It abolished the death penalty","It established the Supreme Court"],a:1,exp:"The Human Rights Act 1998 incorporated the European Convention on Human Rights into UK domestic law, allowing people to enforce their Convention rights in UK courts."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What does 'proportional representation' mean?",o:["One MP per constituency regardless of population","Parties receive seats roughly in proportion to their share of votes","Only the top two candidates go to a run-off vote","Voters rank candidates in order of preference"],a:1,exp:"Under proportional representation, parties win seats in rough proportion to the votes they receive nationally. This contrasts with first past the post, used in UK general elections."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"Who is the head of state of the United Kingdom?",o:["The Prime Minister","The Lord Chancellor","The monarch","The Speaker of the House of Commons"],a:2,exp:"The monarch is the UK's head of state. The Prime Minister is the head of government. Currently King Charles III is the head of state."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is a 'free press' and why is it important in the UK?",o:["Newspapers distributed at no cost to the public","Media that operates independently of government control — a check on power","A press regulated entirely by the government","State-funded journalism"],a:1,exp:"A free press means the media can report and comment without government censorship or control. It is considered essential to democracy as it holds the government and powerful institutions to account."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is 'Prime Minister's Questions' (PMQs)?",o:["A TV quiz show about politics","A weekly session where MPs question the Prime Minister in the House of Commons","A monthly press conference the PM holds for journalists","An annual debate between party leaders"],a:1,exp:"PMQs takes place every Wednesday when Parliament is sitting. MPs — particularly the Leader of the Opposition — question the Prime Minister. It is a key form of parliamentary accountability."},

// ── VALUES & SOCIETY (harder) ─────────────────────────────
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What does 'tolerance' mean as a British value?",o:["Agreeing with everyone's views","Accepting that others have the right to different opinions, faiths and lifestyles","Ignoring illegal behaviour if it is culturally motivated","Enforcing one set of beliefs on everyone"],a:1,exp:"Tolerance means accepting that others have the right to hold different views, practise different religions and live differently — as long as they stay within the law and respect others' rights."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What are the three branches of the UK state?",o:["The Crown, Parliament and the Military","The Legislature, the Executive and the Judiciary","The Lords, the Commons and the Monarch","The Home Office, Foreign Office and Treasury"],a:1,exp:"The three branches are: the Legislature (Parliament — makes laws), the Executive (government — implements laws) and the Judiciary (courts — interprets laws). Their separation prevents any one branch having too much power."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What is the significance of the Bill of Rights 1689?",o:["It gave all men the right to vote","It established that Parliament was supreme over the Crown and guaranteed certain civil rights","It created the position of Prime Minister","It united England and Scotland"],a:1,exp:"The Bill of Rights 1689, following the Glorious Revolution, confirmed Parliament's supremacy over the Crown, established free elections, freedom of speech in Parliament, and prohibited cruel punishments."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What does 'equality before the law' mean?",o:["Everyone receives the same sentence for the same crime","The law applies equally to all people regardless of wealth, status or background","Only citizens have full legal rights","Judges must always side with the less wealthy party"],a:1,exp:"Equality before the law means the same laws apply to everyone — rich or poor, powerful or ordinary. No one, including the government, is above the law."},

// ── A MODERN SOCIETY (harder) ─────────────────────────────
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What is the Notting Hill Carnival?",o:["A traditional English harvest festival in west London","Europe's largest street festival, celebrating Caribbean culture","An annual film awards ceremony held in London","A celebration of the Norman conquest"],a:1,exp:"The Notting Hill Carnival, held annually in London on the August bank holiday, is Europe's largest street festival. It celebrates Caribbean — particularly Trinidadian — culture and heritage."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What famous sporting event is held at Epsom Downs each June?",o:["The Grand National","The Cheltenham Gold Cup","The Derby","The Royal Ascot"],a:2,exp:"The Derby is one of Britain's most famous flat horse races, held at Epsom Downs in Surrey each June. It is part of the Classic series of races and attracts huge crowds."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"Which Scottish city is famous for its annual International Festival and Fringe?",o:["Glasgow","Aberdeen","Inverness","Edinburgh"],a:3,exp:"Edinburgh hosts the world-famous Edinburgh International Festival and the Edinburgh Fringe — the world's largest arts festival — every August, attracting performers and visitors from around the globe."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What is the name of the annual flower show held in Chelsea, London?",o:["The Hampton Court Show","The Royal Horticultural Show","The Chelsea Flower Show","The Kew Gardens Festival"],a:2,exp:"The Chelsea Flower Show, organised by the Royal Horticultural Society (RHS), is held annually in the grounds of the Royal Hospital Chelsea. It is the world's most famous flower show."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"Which famous structure, completed in 1894, spans the River Thames in London?",o:["Waterloo Bridge","Westminster Bridge","London Bridge","Tower Bridge"],a:3,exp:"Tower Bridge, completed in 1894, is one of London's most iconic landmarks. Its distinctive Victorian Gothic towers and bascule design make it instantly recognisable worldwide."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"Who wrote 'A Brief History of Time', a landmark popular science book?",o:["Richard Dawkins","Tim Berners-Lee","Stephen Hawking","James Watson"],a:2,exp:"Stephen Hawking (1942--2018), the Cambridge physicist, wrote 'A Brief History of Time' (1988), which brought complex cosmology to a mass audience. Despite severe disability, he made groundbreaking contributions to physics."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"Who invented the World Wide Web in 1989?",o:["Alan Turing","Tim Berners-Lee","Clive Sinclair","James Dyson"],a:1,exp:"Sir Tim Berners-Lee, a British scientist working at CERN, invented the World Wide Web in 1989. He proposed a system of information sharing using hypertext that became the foundation of the modern internet."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What did Alan Turing contribute to British history?",o:["He invented the telephone","He pioneered computing and helped crack the German Enigma code in WW2","He discovered the structure of DNA","He designed the Spitfire aircraft"],a:1,exp:"Alan Turing (1912--1954) was a pioneering mathematician and computer scientist. His work breaking the German Enigma cipher at Bletchley Park during WW2 is credited with significantly shortening the war."},

// ── NATIONS & SYMBOLS (harder) ───────────────────────────
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the name of the Scottish national epic poem, written by Robert Burns?",o:["The Lady of the Lake","Tam o' Shanter","Auld Lang Syne","The Bruce"],a:1,exp:"'Tam o' Shanter' (1790) is Robert Burns's best-known narrative poem. Burns (1759--1796) is Scotland's national poet, celebrated on Burns Night (25 January) each year."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is 'Burns Night'?",o:["A Scottish festival held on 25 January celebrating poet Robert Burns","A bonfire night tradition unique to Scotland","A memorial for those who died in the Battle of Culloden","A harvest festival in the Scottish Highlands"],a:0,exp:"Burns Night (25 January) celebrates the life and poetry of Robert Burns. Festivities include a Burns Supper with haggis, neeps and tatties, recitation of Burns's poems, and toasts."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"On what date is St David's Day celebrated?",o:["17 March","1 March","23 April","30 November"],a:1,exp:"St David's Day is celebrated on 1 March in Wales. St David (Dewi Sant) is the patron saint of Wales. People traditionally wear daffodils or leeks on this day."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the highest mountain in the UK?",o:["Scafell Pike","Snowdon","Ben Nevis","Slieve Donard"],a:2,exp:"Ben Nevis in Scotland (1,345m) is the highest mountain in the UK. Scafell Pike is the highest in England, Snowdon in Wales, and Slieve Donard in Northern Ireland."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the longest river in the UK?",o:["The Thames","The Severn","The Trent","The Clyde"],a:1,exp:"The River Severn (354km) is the longest river in the UK, flowing through Wales and England into the Bristol Channel. The Thames (346km) is the longest river entirely within England."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the capital city of Wales?",o:["Swansea","Newport","Caernarfon","Cardiff"],a:3,exp:"Cardiff (Caerdydd in Welsh) is the capital city of Wales and its largest city. It became the official capital in 1955."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the capital city of Scotland?",o:["Glasgow","Dundee","Edinburgh","Stirling"],a:2,exp:"Edinburgh is the capital of Scotland, home to the Scottish Parliament and Edinburgh Castle. Glasgow is Scotland's largest city but not its capital."},

// ── EVERYDAY LIFE (harder) ────────────────────────────────
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is the non-emergency police number in the UK?",o:["999","112","101","111"],a:2,exp:"101 is the non-emergency police number for reporting crime or incidents that don't require an immediate response. 999 is for emergencies only."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"At what age can you drive a car in the UK?",o:["16","17","18","21"],a:1,exp:"You can drive a car on public roads from age 17 in the UK, provided you have a provisional licence. You can apply for a provisional licence from age 15 years and 9 months."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What does it mean to 'stand' in a UK election?",o:["To campaign for another candidate","To put yourself forward as a candidate","To vote in person rather than by post","To serve as a polling station officer"],a:1,exp:"'Standing' in an election means putting yourself forward as a candidate. Candidates 'stand' for election; voters 'vote' for them. Any UK citizen aged 18+ can stand for most elected offices."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is the purpose of a National Insurance number?",o:["To access the NHS","To track your tax and National Insurance contributions throughout your working life","To register to vote","To prove your identity at the border"],a:1,exp:"Your NI number is a unique identifier ensuring your tax and NI contributions are correctly recorded. It is essential for working, claiming benefits, and receiving a state pension."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"Which body regulates financial services in the UK?",o:["The Bank of England","The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA)","The Treasury","The Competition and Markets Authority"],a:1,exp:"The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) regulates financial services firms and markets in the UK, protecting consumers and ensuring honest, fair markets. The Bank of England has separate regulatory responsibilities."},

// ── BRITISH HISTORY (early & medieval) ───────────────────────
{cat:"British History",q:"When did the Romans first invade Britain?",o:["55 BC, under Julius Caesar","43 AD, under Emperor Claudius","122 AD, when Hadrian's Wall was built","410 AD, when they left"],a:0,exp:"Julius Caesar made the first Roman expedition to Britain in 55 BC (and again in 54 BC), but did not conquer it. The full Roman conquest began in 43 AD under Emperor Claudius."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Who was Boudicca?",o:["A Roman empress who governed Britain","A Celtic queen of the Iceni tribe who led a major revolt against Roman rule around 60–61 AD","A Saxon princess who unified the English kingdoms","A Viking queen who settled in northern England"],a:1,exp:"Boudicca was queen of the Iceni tribe in eastern Britain. She led a revolt against Roman occupation around 60–61 AD, destroying Colchester, London and St Albans before being defeated."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Who were the Anglo-Saxons?",o:["Roman soldiers who stayed in Britain","Germanic tribes from northern Europe who settled in England after the Romans left around 410 AD","Viking raiders from Scandinavia","Celtic tribes from Gaul"],a:1,exp:"The Anglo-Saxons were Germanic tribes — Angles, Saxons and Jutes — who settled in England after the Romans left. They gave England its name ('Angle-land') and established the kingdoms that preceded Norman England."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Who was King Alfred the Great?",o:["A Norman king who conquered England in 1066","A Viking king who ruled all of England","A Saxon king of Wessex who defended England against the Vikings and promoted learning","The first Tudor monarch"],a:2,exp:"Alfred the Great (849–899) was King of Wessex who successfully resisted the Viking invasions. He promoted education and literacy and is the only English monarch called 'the Great'."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the feudal system introduced by the Normans?",o:["A system of elected local government","A hierarchy where the king owned all land and granted it to nobles in exchange for military service, with peasants at the bottom","A trading system between English towns","A church-based court system"],a:1,exp:"The feudal system placed the king at the top, nobles (barons and knights) below him, and peasants at the bottom. Land was held in exchange for loyalty and military service."},

// ── BRITISH HISTORY (Tudor to Victorian) ─────────────────────
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the significance of the Spanish Armada in 1588?",o:["Spain successfully invaded England","A Spanish fleet sent to invade Protestant England was defeated by the English navy and storms","Spain blockaded English ports for two years","The Spanish captured the English fleet"],a:1,exp:"Philip II of Spain sent an Armada of 130 ships to invade England in 1588. It was defeated by the English fleet (vice-admiral: Sir Francis Drake) and storms. The victory boosted English national confidence."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Who was Elizabeth I?",o:["A Stuart queen who converted England to Catholicism","A Tudor queen (1558–1603) whose reign saw exploration, artistic flowering and the defeat of the Spanish Armada","A Norman queen who oversaw the Domesday Book","The first queen to rule England alone"],a:1,exp:"Elizabeth I (1558–1603) was one of England's greatest monarchs. Her long reign saw the defeat of the Spanish Armada, the flourishing of arts (Shakespeare, Marlowe) and significant overseas exploration."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the Gunpowder Plot of 1605?",o:["A Puritan attempt to assassinate Queen Elizabeth I","A failed Catholic conspiracy to blow up Parliament and kill King James I — now commemorated on Bonfire Night, 5 November","A Protestant plot to overthrow Mary I","A Scottish plot against James VI"],a:1,exp:"The Gunpowder Plot was a failed conspiracy led by Robert Catesby (with Guy Fawkes guarding the gunpowder) to blow up Parliament and kill James I on 5 November 1605. It is commemorated every year with bonfires and fireworks."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the Restoration of 1660?",o:["The restoration of the Catholic Church in England","Charles II returned from exile and the monarchy was restored after the Commonwealth period under Oliver Cromwell","Scotland was restored to independence","The restoration of Parliament after the Civil War"],a:1,exp:"After Oliver Cromwell's death, Parliament invited Charles II back from exile. The monarchy was restored in 1660, ending the republican Commonwealth that had ruled since 1649."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the significance of the Battle of Waterloo (1815)?",o:["Britain defeated the French navy","Napoleon Bonaparte was finally defeated by the Duke of Wellington and Prussian forces, ending the Napoleonic Wars","Britain won the Seven Years War","The French Revolution ended"],a:1,exp:"At Waterloo (18 June 1815), the Duke of Wellington and Prussian forces under Blücher defeated Napoleon. It ended the Napoleonic Wars and cemented Britain as the leading world power of the 19th century."},
{cat:"British History",q:"When did Britain abolish the transatlantic slave trade?",o:["1772","1807","1833","1865"],a:1,exp:"The Slave Trade Act 1807 abolished the trade in enslaved people across the British Empire. The Slavery Abolition Act 1833 then freed enslaved people throughout most of the Empire. William Wilberforce was a leading abolitionist."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the Great Exhibition of 1851?",o:["A trade fair displaying only British goods","An international exhibition in Hyde Park celebrating industrial achievement, masterminded by Prince Albert","A celebration of Queen Victoria's coronation","A military parade for British victories"],a:1,exp:"The Great Exhibition (1851) was the world's first international exhibition, held in the Crystal Palace in Hyde Park, London. Organised largely by Prince Albert, it showcased Britain's industrial and imperial power to the world."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Who was Florence Nightingale?",o:["A Victorian novelist","A pioneer of modern nursing who transformed care during the Crimean War using hygiene and statistics","The first woman elected to Parliament","A leading suffragette"],a:1,exp:"Florence Nightingale (1820–1910) became famous during the Crimean War (1853–56) for transforming hospital care through rigorous hygiene. She is considered the founder of modern nursing and used statistics to argue for reform."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Who was Isambard Kingdom Brunel?",o:["A Victorian Prime Minister","A pioneering engineer who designed the Great Western Railway, Clifton Suspension Bridge and SS Great Britain","A scientist who developed the theory of evolution","A Scottish inventor who made the first working steam engine"],a:1,exp:"Isambard Kingdom Brunel (1806–1859) was one of the greatest engineers of the Industrial Revolution, responsible for the Great Western Railway, the Clifton Suspension Bridge and the SS Great Britain steamship."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What were the Corn Laws and why were they repealed?",o:["Laws requiring farmers to grow corn — repealed after poor harvests","Tariffs on imported grain keeping bread prices high — repealed in 1846 by PM Robert Peel to allow free trade and lower food costs","Laws preventing wool exports — repealed to boost trade","Laws regulating brewing — repealed after public protests"],a:1,exp:"The Corn Laws kept bread prices artificially high by taxing grain imports, benefiting landowners at the expense of the urban poor. PM Robert Peel repealed them in 1846 — a landmark victory for free trade and the growing industrial working class."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Who was Charles Dickens?",o:["A Victorian politician who reformed child labour laws","A novelist whose works — including Oliver Twist and A Christmas Carol — highlighted poverty and social inequality in Victorian England","A Scottish poet who wrote about industrialisation","A scientist who pioneered the theory of evolution"],a:1,exp:"Charles Dickens (1812–1870) is one of the greatest English novelists. His works, including Oliver Twist, David Copperfield, Bleak House and A Christmas Carol, exposed poverty and injustice in Victorian society."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the significance of Indian independence in 1947?",o:["India remained part of the British Empire","India and Pakistan gained independence on 15 August 1947 — a major step in the decline of the British Empire","India became a republic in 1947","Only Pakistan gained independence in 1947"],a:1,exp:"India gained independence on 15 August 1947, partitioned into India and Pakistan. It was one of the most significant events in the end of the British Empire and the modern history of South Asia."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the significance of the 1945 general election?",o:["Churchill won a landslide","Labour under Clement Attlee won a landslide and proceeded to build the welfare state and found the NHS","The Liberal Party won for the first time","It was the first election where women could vote"],a:1,exp:"The 1945 general election saw a landslide for Labour under Clement Attlee, defeating Churchill despite his wartime popularity. The new government created the welfare state, founded the NHS (1948), and nationalised key industries."},
{cat:"British History",q:"Which famous Victorian engineer built the Clifton Suspension Bridge?",o:["George Stephenson","James Watt","Isambard Kingdom Brunel","Thomas Telford"],a:2,exp:"Isambard Kingdom Brunel designed the Clifton Suspension Bridge across the Avon Gorge in Bristol. Construction began in 1831 and was completed posthumously in 1864, five years after Brunel's death."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the 'Blitz' during World War II?",o:["The Allied invasion of Normandy","A German bombing campaign against British cities, especially London, in 1940–41","The Battle of Britain air campaign","The German naval blockade of British ports"],a:1,exp:"The Blitz was a German bombing campaign against Britain from September 1940 to May 1941, targeting London and other major cities. Tens of thousands of civilians were killed, but British morale held."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What did the Beveridge Report (1942) recommend?",o:["A plan for post-war military alliances","A comprehensive welfare state — social security 'from the cradle to the grave' — tackling Want, Disease, Ignorance, Squalor and Idleness","The nationalisation of all British industry","A new written constitution for Britain"],a:1,exp:"The Beveridge Report (1942), written by William Beveridge, proposed tackling five 'giant evils': Want, Disease, Ignorance, Squalor and Idleness. It laid the foundations for the post-war welfare state, including the NHS and National Insurance."},
{cat:"British History",q:"What was the Battle of Britain (1940)?",o:["Britain's invasion of France to liberate Paris","The RAF's successful defence of Britain against the German Luftwaffe's air campaign — preventing a German invasion","Britain's defeat of the German navy in the North Sea","The Allied capture of Berlin"],a:1,exp:"The Battle of Britain (summer 1940) saw the RAF successfully defend British skies against sustained Luftwaffe attacks. Churchill called it the RAF's 'finest hour'. The German failure to gain air superiority prevented the planned invasion of Britain."},

// ── GOVERNMENT & LAW (new) ────────────────────────────────────
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the minimum voting age in UK general elections?",o:["16","17","18","21"],a:2,exp:"You must be 18 to vote in UK general elections. Scotland and Wales have lowered the voting age to 16 for their devolved elections, but UK-wide general elections require voters to be 18."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"How many MPs sit in the House of Commons?",o:["450","550","650","750"],a:2,exp:"There are 650 Members of Parliament (MPs) in the House of Commons, each representing one constituency. General elections are held to elect all 650 seats simultaneously."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is 'Royal Assent'?",o:["The monarch's permission to hold a general election","The formal approval by the monarch that turns a bill passed by Parliament into law (an Act of Parliament)","The monarch's appointment of the Prime Minister","The right to use the Royal Arms"],a:1,exp:"Royal Assent is when the monarch formally approves a bill passed by both Houses of Parliament, making it law. In practice, Royal Assent is always granted — the last time it was refused was in 1708."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is a party manifesto?",o:["A secret government document","A document published before an election setting out a party's policies and promises to voters","A formal complaint to Parliament","A bill before it becomes law"],a:1,exp:"A manifesto is a public document published by a political party before an election, setting out its policies and promises. Voters can use manifestos to compare parties. A winning party is expected to implement its manifesto."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the role of the Cabinet?",o:["A group of civil servants who run the country day-to-day","Senior ministers — usually heads of government departments — who meet to agree government policy, chaired by the Prime Minister","The committee of MPs that scrutinises the government","The group of advisers in 10 Downing Street"],a:1,exp:"The Cabinet is the main decision-making body of government, comprising around 20–25 senior ministers. It meets weekly to decide policy. All Cabinet ministers are expected to support decisions publicly — 'collective responsibility'."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the role of Select Committees in Parliament?",o:["They write new laws","Groups of MPs (and Lords) that scrutinise the work, spending and policies of government departments","They elect the Prime Minister","They decide criminal sentences"],a:1,exp:"Select Committees are groups of MPs that examine specific government departments (e.g. Health, Treasury). They call ministers and civil servants to give evidence, investigate policy, and publish reports. They are a key accountability mechanism."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the Chancellor of the Exchequer responsible for?",o:["Foreign affairs and diplomacy","Managing the economy and public finances, including the annual Budget","Overseeing the legal system","Commanding the armed forces"],a:1,exp:"The Chancellor of the Exchequer heads the Treasury and is responsible for economic and fiscal policy. Each year, the Chancellor presents the Budget — the government's plans for taxation and public spending."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the Home Secretary responsible for?",o:["Foreign policy","Immigration, policing, national security and prisons","Economic policy","Education"],a:1,exp:"The Home Secretary heads the Home Office, responsible for immigration and border control, national security, police funding, and the prison and probation service. It is one of the four great offices of state."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is a magistrates' court?",o:["The highest criminal court in England","A court dealing with less serious criminal offences — the vast majority of criminal cases begin here","A court only for young offenders","A civil court for contract disputes"],a:1,exp:"Magistrates' courts deal with summary (less serious) offences and preliminary hearings for more serious cases. About 95% of criminal cases in England and Wales are handled entirely by magistrates, who are usually unpaid volunteers."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is judicial independence?",o:["Judges can pass laws without Parliament","Judges decide cases based solely on the law and evidence, free from political interference — ensuring fair, impartial justice","Judges are independent of all public scrutiny","Only the judiciary can propose constitutional changes"],a:1,exp:"Judicial independence means courts are free from political interference by the government. It is a cornerstone of the rule of law, ensuring citizens can challenge even the government in court and receive impartial justice."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the purpose of the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS)?",o:["It manages the Royal Family's finances","It decides whether to prosecute criminal cases in England and Wales based on evidence and the public interest","It runs the Crown Court","It provides legal aid to defendants"],a:1,exp:"The CPS prosecutes criminal cases in England and Wales. It reviews evidence gathered by the police and decides whether there is enough to charge someone and whether prosecution is in the public interest. It is independent of the police."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What does it mean to 'register to vote' in the UK?",o:["Joining a political party","Adding your name to the Electoral Register — required before you can vote in elections","Applying for a postal vote","Paying a fee to participate in democracy"],a:1,exp:"To vote you must be on the Electoral Register. You register with your local council (online or by post). If you're not registered, you cannot vote. Registration is open to UK citizens, qualifying Commonwealth citizens and EU citizens (for some elections)."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the role of the Foreign Secretary?",o:["Managing the economy","Leading the UK's foreign policy and international relations on behalf of the government","Overseeing immigration","Managing the NHS"],a:1,exp:"The Foreign Secretary (Secretary of State for Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Affairs) is responsible for the UK's foreign policy, diplomatic relations, and overseas development. It is one of the four great offices of state."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is meant by 'collective Cabinet responsibility'?",o:["All Cabinet ministers are collectively responsible for their department's spending","All Cabinet ministers must publicly support government decisions, even if they disagreed in Cabinet","Cabinet ministers share a collective salary","All ministers are equally responsible for the PM's decisions"],a:1,exp:"Collective Cabinet responsibility means all ministers must publicly support Cabinet decisions, regardless of private disagreements. A minister who cannot support a decision is expected to resign. This maintains a united government front."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the purpose of a 'Green Paper' in the UK?",o:["An environmental policy document","A consultation document where the government sets out proposals and invites public debate before deciding on policy","A final piece of legislation ready to become law","A document from the House of Lords"],a:1,exp:"A Green Paper is a consultative document where the government sets out proposals for debate. It is followed by a White Paper (firmer proposals) and then, if appropriate, legislation. Green Papers invite public and parliamentary comment."},
{cat:"Government & Law",q:"What is the Northern Ireland Assembly?",o:["The UK Parliament's committee on Northern Ireland","The devolved legislature of Northern Ireland, established under the Good Friday Agreement (1998), with powers over health, education and other devolved matters","A local council for Belfast","A cross-border body between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland"],a:1,exp:"The Northern Ireland Assembly is the devolved legislature established by the Good Friday Agreement (1998). It has powers over devolved matters such as health, education and agriculture. It uses a power-sharing system requiring unionist and nationalist participation."},

// ── VALUES & SOCIETY (new) ────────────────────────────────────
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What is the minimum age to vote in UK general elections?",o:["16","17","18","21"],a:2,exp:"The voting age for UK general elections is 18. Scotland and Wales allow 16-year-olds to vote in their devolved elections. There is ongoing debate about whether to lower the UK-wide voting age to 16."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What is the Equality Act 2010?",o:["A law requiring equal pay for men and women only","A law protecting people from discrimination on the basis of protected characteristics including age, disability, race, sex, religion and sexual orientation","A law requiring equal representation in Parliament","A law requiring equal access to public services"],a:1,exp:"The Equality Act 2010 protects people from discrimination on nine protected characteristics: age, disability, gender reassignment, marriage/civil partnership, pregnancy, race, religion or belief, sex, and sexual orientation."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What does 'freedom of religion' mean as a British value?",o:["Everyone must follow the Church of England","People may follow any religion or none, and may worship and express their beliefs freely within the law","Only registered religions are permitted","Religious freedom only applies to those born in the UK"],a:1,exp:"Freedom of religion or belief is a fundamental right in the UK. People are free to practise any religion or no religion, change their faith, and express their beliefs — within the limits of the law."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What is parliamentary sovereignty?",o:["The Parliament building is specially protected","Parliament is the supreme law-making authority — no court or other body can override what Parliament enacts","The monarch controls all Parliamentary decisions","Parliament is independent of all public accountability"],a:1,exp:"Parliamentary sovereignty means Parliament is the supreme legal authority in the UK. It can make or unmake any law. No Parliament can bind its successors, and courts interpret but cannot override Acts of Parliament."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What is a 'pressure group' in British politics?",o:["A group of MPs who always vote together","An organisation that campaigns to influence government policy on specific issues without seeking to form a government","A group of voters organised in a marginal constituency","A secret government advisory body"],a:1,exp:"Pressure groups (or interest groups) campaign on specific issues — for example environmental organisations, trade unions or business groups. They lobby government, Parliament and the public to influence policy without standing for election themselves."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What does 'the rule of law' guarantee for individuals?",o:["That the government always wins in court","That everyone — including the government — is subject to the law and can seek justice in independent courts","That only citizens have legal rights","That laws can only be changed by referendum"],a:1,exp:"The rule of law guarantees that laws apply equally to everyone — no one, including government ministers, is above the law. If the government acts unlawfully, citizens can challenge it in independent courts through 'judicial review'."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What is the role of voluntary work in British society?",o:["It replaces all government services","Volunteering plays a vital role — millions of people give time to charities, community organisations and mutual aid groups, strengthening communities","Voluntary work is only done by retired people","It is required by law for unemployed people"],a:1,exp:"Voluntary work is a cornerstone of British civic life. Millions of people volunteer in charities, community groups, sports clubs, hospitals and many other settings. The voluntary sector is distinct from the government and private sectors."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"What are the two Houses of Parliament?",o:["The Senate and the Assembly","The House of Commons and the House of Lords","The Upper House and the Lower Chamber","The Crown and Parliament"],a:1,exp:"Parliament consists of the House of Commons (elected MPs) and the House of Lords (appointed peers and bishops). Bills must pass both Houses before receiving Royal Assent. The Commons has ultimate authority."},
{cat:"Values & Society",q:"Who is the head of the Church of England?",o:["The Pope","The Archbishop of Canterbury","The monarch","The Prime Minister"],a:2,exp:"The monarch is the Supreme Governor of the Church of England. The Archbishop of Canterbury is its spiritual leader. This role dates from Henry VIII's break with Rome in the 1530s."},

// ── A MODERN SOCIETY (new) ────────────────────────────────────
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What are the four countries of the United Kingdom?",o:["England, Scotland, Wales and the Republic of Ireland","England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland","England, Scotland, Wales and the Isle of Man","England, Scotland, Wales and the Channel Islands"],a:1,exp:"The United Kingdom consists of England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland. The Republic of Ireland is a separate, independent country. The Isle of Man and Channel Islands are Crown Dependencies, not part of the UK."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"Approximately what is the population of the United Kingdom?",o:["Around 47 million","Around 57 million","Around 67 million","Around 80 million"],a:2,exp:"The UK population is approximately 67 million. England is by far the most populous country (around 56 million), followed by Scotland (about 5.5 million), Wales (about 3.2 million) and Northern Ireland (about 1.9 million)."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What is the 'Windrush generation'?",o:["Engineers who built the UK's post-war motorway network","People from the Caribbean who came to the UK from 1948 onwards, invited to help address post-war labour shortages","A group of Welsh miners who moved to London after the collieries closed","German prisoners of war who stayed in Britain after 1945"],a:1,exp:"The Windrush generation refers to the hundreds of thousands of people who came from Caribbean Commonwealth countries from 1948. The Empire Windrush was the first ship to bring large numbers. They contributed enormously to the NHS, transport and many other sectors."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"Who invented the World Wide Web in 1989?",o:["Alan Turing","Bill Gates","Tim Berners-Lee","Clive Sinclair"],a:2,exp:"Sir Tim Berners-Lee, a British scientist working at CERN, invented the World Wide Web in 1989. His proposal for an information-sharing system using hypertext became the foundation of the modern internet."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What is the Grand National?",o:["A cross-country running race","A famous annual horse race held at Aintree, near Liverpool, known for its challenging fences","A cycling race held in Scotland","The UK's biggest motor racing event"],a:1,exp:"The Grand National is one of the most famous horse races in the world, held annually at Aintree Racecourse near Liverpool. It features a large field of horses over a challenging course with distinctive fences and is watched by millions."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What sport is the Wimbledon Championship associated with?",o:["Cricket","Rugby","Tennis","Athletics"],a:2,exp:"Wimbledon (the All England Lawn Tennis Championships) is the world's oldest and most prestigious tennis Grand Slam, held annually in London. It is famous for its grass courts, strict dress code and tradition of strawberries and cream."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What is 'Hogmanay'?",o:["A traditional Scottish meat dish","The Scottish New Year celebration on 31 December and 1 January, marked by large public gatherings and first-footing","A Welsh harvest festival","A Northern Irish traditional music festival"],a:1,exp:"Hogmanay is the Scottish New Year celebration. Edinburgh's Hogmanay is one of the world's largest New Year parties. Traditions include first-footing (being the first to enter a neighbour's home after midnight) and singing Auld Lang Syne."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"Which British author wrote the Harry Potter series?",o:["Agatha Christie","Roald Dahl","J.K. Rowling","Ian Fleming"],a:2,exp:"J.K. Rowling wrote the seven Harry Potter novels, beginning with Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (1997). The series has sold over 500 million copies worldwide and is one of the best-selling book series in history."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"Who discovered the structure of DNA?",o:["Isaac Newton and Robert Hooke","Francis Crick, James Watson — with crucial X-ray work by Rosalind Franklin","Charles Darwin and Thomas Huxley","Stephen Hawking and Roger Penrose"],a:1,exp:"The double helix structure of DNA was discovered in 1953 by Francis Crick and James Watson, building on X-ray crystallography work by Rosalind Franklin. Crick and Watson (with Maurice Wilkins) received the Nobel Prize in 1962."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What is the Tate Modern?",o:["A modern government building in Westminster","A major modern and contemporary art gallery in London, housed in a former power station on the Thames","A science museum in Manchester","A theatre in the West End"],a:1,exp:"Tate Modern is one of the world's most visited art galleries, opened in 2000 in the converted Bankside Power Station on the South Bank in London. Admission to the main collection is free."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What is the Chelsea Flower Show?",o:["A garden party at Buckingham Palace","An annual horticultural show held in the grounds of the Royal Hospital Chelsea, run by the Royal Horticultural Society","A weekly flower market in west London","A national competition for amateur gardeners"],a:1,exp:"The Chelsea Flower Show is held each May in the grounds of the Royal Hospital Chelsea by the Royal Horticultural Society (RHS). It is the world's most famous flower show, showcasing innovative garden designs and plants."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What does the National Trust do?",o:["Manages the national debt","A charity that protects historic buildings, coastline and countryside across England, Wales and Northern Ireland for the public to enjoy","A government body managing national parks","A bank offering savings accounts"],a:1,exp:"The National Trust is a conservation charity founded in 1895. It protects and opens to the public hundreds of historic houses, gardens, nature reserves and miles of coastline across England, Wales and Northern Ireland. It is one of the UK's largest charities."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What is the significance of the Edinburgh Festival each August?",o:["It is Scotland's national sporting event","Edinburgh hosts the world's largest arts festival — the Edinburgh Fringe — alongside the International Festival, attracting performers and visitors from around the world","It is a traditional Highland games event","It celebrates the Battle of Flodden"],a:1,exp:"Each August, Edinburgh becomes the world's arts capital. The Edinburgh International Festival (founded 1947) and the Edinburgh Fringe (the world's largest arts festival) together attract thousands of shows and hundreds of thousands of visitors from around the globe."},
{cat:"A Modern Society",q:"What is the significance of the NHS to British society?",o:["It is a private healthcare network","The NHS — founded in 1948 — provides free healthcare at the point of use to all UK residents and is one of the most cherished institutions in British life","It only provides emergency services","It is run by local councils"],a:1,exp:"The NHS (National Health Service), founded in 1948, is one of the world's largest publicly funded health services. It provides comprehensive healthcare free at the point of use to all UK residents, funded by taxation. It is widely regarded as a defining British institution."},

// ── NATIONS & SYMBOLS (new) ──────────────────────────────────
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What are the four patron saints of the UK nations?",o:["St George, St Andrew, St David, St Peter","St George (England), St Andrew (Scotland), St David (Wales), St Patrick (Northern Ireland/Ireland)","St George, St Michael, St David, St Columba","St Edmund, St Andrew, St David, St Patrick"],a:1,exp:"England's patron saint is St George (23 April), Scotland's is St Andrew (30 November), Wales's is St David (1 March), and Northern Ireland/Ireland's is St Patrick (17 March)."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the capital city of Northern Ireland?",o:["Londonderry/Derry","Armagh","Lisburn","Belfast"],a:3,exp:"Belfast is the capital and largest city of Northern Ireland. It is famous for its Victorian architecture, linen and shipbuilding heritage (the Titanic was built there) and the Titanic Belfast museum."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What does the red dragon on the Welsh flag symbolise?",o:["Roman occupation of Wales","An ancient Welsh symbol from mythology and history","It was added to honour Henry VIII","Wales's coal mining heritage"],a:1,exp:"The red dragon (Y Ddraig Goch) has been associated with Wales since the early medieval period. The current Welsh flag — a red dragon on a green and white background — became official in 1959 and is one of the world's oldest national flags."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the significance of 11 November in the UK?",o:["Bonfire Night","Remembrance Day — marking the armistice ending WW1 in 1918, observed with a two-minute silence at 11am","The monarch's official birthday","St Andrew's Day"],a:1,exp:"Remembrance Day (11 November) marks the armistice that ended the First World War at 11am on 11 November 1918. A two-minute silence is held at 11am. Remembrance Sunday (nearest Sunday) sees a national service at the Cenotaph on Whitehall."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is 'Bonfire Night' and when is it celebrated?",o:["A midsummer festival in June","5 November — celebrating the failure of the Gunpowder Plot in 1605, with bonfires and fireworks across the UK","A harvest festival in October","A Viking fire ceremony held in January"],a:1,exp:"Bonfire Night (Guy Fawkes Night) on 5 November commemorates the failure of the Gunpowder Plot of 1605. It is celebrated with bonfires, fireworks and the burning of 'guy' effigies across the UK."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the national animal of Scotland?",o:["The golden eagle","The stag","The unicorn","The red deer"],a:2,exp:"The unicorn is Scotland's national animal. It appears on the Scottish coat of arms and on the royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom (alongside the English lion). The unicorn historically symbolised power and independence."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the Cenotaph and where is it?",o:["A war memorial in Edinburgh's Princes Street","The national war memorial on Whitehall in London, the focus of Remembrance Sunday ceremonies","A monument in Cardiff Bay","A memorial on the White Cliffs of Dover"],a:1,exp:"The Cenotaph on Whitehall, London, is the UK's central war memorial. It was unveiled in 1920. On Remembrance Sunday, the monarch, government, military and public gather there to lay wreaths and honour those who died in conflict."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the highest mountain in England?",o:["Ben Nevis","Snowdon","Scafell Pike","Helvellyn"],a:2,exp:"Scafell Pike (978m) in the Lake District, Cumbria, is the highest mountain in England. Ben Nevis (Scotland) is the highest in the UK, Snowdon (Wales) and Slieve Donard (Northern Ireland) are the highest in their countries."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the longest river in the UK?",o:["The Thames","The Severn","The Trent","The Clyde"],a:1,exp:"The River Severn (354km) is the longest river in the UK, flowing from Wales through England to the Bristol Channel. The Thames (346km) is the longest river entirely within England."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What language is spoken in parts of Scotland alongside English?",o:["Welsh","Cornish","Scottish Gaelic","Manx"],a:2,exp:"Scottish Gaelic is spoken by around 57,000 people, mainly in the Highlands and Islands. Scots (a Germanic language) is also spoken across Scotland. Both are officially recognised alongside English."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is St David's Day and when is it celebrated?",o:["The English national day on 23 April","The Welsh national day celebrated on 1 March, honouring the patron saint of Wales","The Scottish national day on 30 November","The Northern Irish national day on 17 March"],a:1,exp:"St David's Day (1 March) is the national day of Wales, honouring St David (Dewi Sant), the patron saint. People traditionally wear daffodils or leeks. It is not a public holiday in Wales, though there is growing pressure to make it one."},
{cat:"Nations & Symbols",q:"What is the significance of the Last Night of the Proms?",o:["The final episode of a popular television series","The closing concert of the BBC Proms season — famous for patriotic music including 'Land of Hope and Glory' and 'Jerusalem'","The closing ceremony of the Edinburgh Fringe","A traditional Scottish celebration"],a:1,exp:"The Last Night of the Proms is the final concert of the BBC Proms season at the Royal Albert Hall. It features patriotic British pieces including 'Land of Hope and Glory', 'Rule, Britannia!' and 'Jerusalem', with a joyful, flag-waving atmosphere."},

// ── EVERYDAY LIFE (new) ──────────────────────────────────────
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What number should you call for non-emergency NHS medical advice?",o:["999","101","111","112"],a:2,exp:"111 provides non-emergency NHS medical advice 24 hours a day. Call if you need urgent medical help but it's not life-threatening. 999 is for genuine emergencies only."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is National Insurance (NI)?",o:["A government home insurance scheme","Contributions by employees and employers that fund state benefits including the NHS, state pension and unemployment support","A private insurance scheme offered by banks","A tax only on the self-employed"],a:1,exp:"National Insurance is a system of contributions paid by employees (from wages), employers and the self-employed. NI funds the NHS, state pension, and social security benefits. Your NI number (a unique reference) tracks your contributions."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What qualifications do students in England typically sit at age 16?",o:["A-levels","GCSEs (General Certificates of Secondary Education)","National Vocational Qualifications only","International Baccalaureate"],a:1,exp:"Students in England usually take GCSEs at age 15–16, in a range of subjects. GCSEs are graded 9–1 (previously A*–G). They are the main qualification at the end of compulsory secondary education."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What are A-levels?",o:["Qualifications taken at age 16","Advanced level qualifications typically taken at age 18, usually required for entry to university","A type of apprenticeship","Vocational qualifications for trade skills"],a:1,exp:"A-levels (Advanced Levels) are academic qualifications usually studied in sixth form or college between ages 16 and 18. They are the main route to university in England, Wales and Northern Ireland. Students typically take 3 A-levels."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is a 'council house' or 'social housing'?",o:["Private housing on council-owned land","Affordable rented accommodation owned and managed by local councils or housing associations","Temporary housing for tourists","Housing provided free to all citizens"],a:1,exp:"Council housing (social housing) is affordable rented accommodation owned by local councils or housing associations. The Right to Buy scheme (introduced 1980) allowed many tenants to purchase their homes at a discount."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is Citizens Advice?",o:["A government immigration advice service","A network of charitable organisations providing free, confidential advice on legal, financial, housing and employment issues","A private legal firm with reduced fees","A government department for welfare claims"],a:1,exp:"Citizens Advice is a network of independent charities providing free, impartial advice on topics including benefits, debt, housing, employment and consumer rights. There are hundreds of local Citizens Advice offices across the UK."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What does it mean to register with a GP?",o:["Paying a fee to access NHS services","Signing up with a local GP surgery so you have a regular doctor — registration is free on the NHS","Applying to a private health insurer","Registering with the Department of Health directly"],a:1,exp:"To access NHS primary care, you register with a local GP (General Practitioner) surgery. Registration is free. You can then see your GP for health concerns, referrals and prescriptions. You should register when you move to a new area."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is the minimum age to buy alcohol in the UK?",o:["16","17","18","21"],a:2,exp:"You must be 18 or over to buy alcohol in the UK. It is also illegal for anyone to buy alcohol for someone under 18 to consume in a licensed premises."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is the legal age of marriage in England and Wales without parental consent?",o:["16","17","18","21"],a:2,exp:"You must be 18 to marry without parental consent in England and Wales. The Marriage and Civil Partnership (Minimum Age) Act 2022 raised the minimum age to 18 in all circumstances, removing the previous exception that allowed 16–17 year olds to marry with parental consent."},
{cat:"Everyday Life",q:"What is the driving test in the UK made up of?",o:["Only a practical driving test","A theory test (including hazard perception) and a practical driving test — both must be passed","Only a written theory test","A medical examination and a practical test"],a:1,exp:"To get a full driving licence in the UK, you must pass both a theory test (multiple-choice questions and hazard perception) and a practical driving test. You must hold a provisional licence and be at least 17."},

// ── UK & WORLD (new) ─────────────────────────────────────────
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What were the D-Day landings of 6 June 1944?",o:["The German invasion of Britain","The Allied amphibious invasion of Normandy, France — the largest seaborne invasion in history, opening a western front against Nazi Germany","The liberation of Paris by British forces alone","Britain's first military action of the Second World War"],a:1,exp:"D-Day (Operation Overlord, 6 June 1944) was the Allied invasion of occupied France. Over 150,000 Allied troops landed on Normandy beaches. The success of the landings opened a western front and led to the liberation of Western Europe."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"When did the UK join the European Economic Community (EEC)?",o:["1957","1963","1973","1979"],a:2,exp:"The UK joined the EEC (now the EU) on 1 January 1973 under Prime Minister Edward Heath. The UK had previously applied twice but was vetoed by France's President de Gaulle in 1963 and 1967."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What was the result of the 2016 Brexit referendum?",o:["The UK voted to remain in the EU by 52% to 48%","The UK voted to leave the EU by 52% to 48%","The result was too close to call and was held again","Only England voted to leave — Scotland and Wales voted to remain"],a:1,exp:"In the June 2016 referendum, 51.9% voted to leave the EU and 48.1% voted to remain. England and Wales voted Leave; Scotland and Northern Ireland voted Remain. The UK formally left the EU on 31 January 2020."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What is the Good Friday Agreement (1998)?",o:["A UK–Ireland fishing agreement","A peace agreement largely ending political violence in Northern Ireland and establishing power-sharing government and cross-border institutions","An agreement to close UK pubs on Good Friday","A trade deal between the UK and Republic of Ireland"],a:1,exp:"The Good Friday Agreement (Belfast Agreement, 1998) brought an end to most of the violence of the Troubles in Northern Ireland. It established a power-sharing Assembly, cross-border bodies between Northern Ireland and the Republic, and normalised UK–Ireland relations."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What is Britain's 'special relationship'?",o:["The relationship between England and Scotland","The uniquely close diplomatic, military, cultural and intelligence ties between the UK and the United States","The UK's privileged trading relationship with the Commonwealth","The UK's unique dual membership of NATO and the UN"],a:1,exp:"The 'special relationship' describes the particularly close ties between the UK and the USA. The term was popularised by Winston Churchill. It encompasses military alliances (including NATO), intelligence sharing (Five Eyes), and close cultural and economic links."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"How many permanent members does the UN Security Council have?",o:["3","5","7","10"],a:1,exp:"The UN Security Council has five permanent members: the United States, Russia, China, France and the United Kingdom. Each has a veto over Security Council resolutions. There are also 10 non-permanent elected members."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What is the Commonwealth of Nations?",o:["A military alliance led by the UK","A voluntary association of 56 independent countries — mostly former British territories — cooperating on trade, development and democratic values","A trading bloc that replaced the EU","Countries that still use the pound sterling"],a:1,exp:"The Commonwealth is a voluntary association of 56 countries. It promotes democracy, development and international cooperation. Members include countries from Africa, Asia, the Caribbean and the Pacific. There are no formal political or economic obligations."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What role does the UK play in the United Nations?",o:["The UK is a non-voting observer","The UK is a founding member and one of five permanent members of the Security Council, with veto power","The UK funds the UN but has no voting rights","The UK joined the UN in 1990"],a:1,exp:"The UK is a founding member of the UN (1945) and one of five permanent members of the Security Council (alongside the US, Russia, China and France). Each permanent member holds veto power over Security Council resolutions."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What does the UK contribute to international development aid?",o:["The UK provides no overseas development aid","The UK is one of the world's largest aid donors, with a legal commitment to spending 0.7% of GNI on official development assistance","The UK only provides military aid to allies","Aid is given only to Commonwealth countries"],a:1,exp:"The International Development (Official Development Assistance Target) Act 2015 required the UK to spend 0.7% of gross national income (GNI) on overseas development aid. The UK is consistently among the world's largest aid donors, supporting health, education and humanitarian relief."},
{cat:"UK & World",q:"What is NATO and when was it founded?",o:["A European trading organisation founded in 1957","The North Atlantic Treaty Organisation — a military alliance founded in 1949, of which the UK is a founding member","A United Nations peacekeeping body","A Commonwealth defence pact"],a:1,exp:"NATO (North Atlantic Treaty Organisation) was founded in 1949. It is a military alliance of (currently 32) member states. Article 5 of the NATO treaty states that an attack on one member is considered an attack on all. The UK is a founding member."},
];
